%[text] # F01: Drawing Molecules from SMILES
%[text] EasyMolKit Basic Tutorial — Layer 1
%[text] 
%[text] How do chemists and researchers communicate molecular structures to others?
%[text] One method is to share images of structural diagrams, but there is a notation that can fully describe ethanol with just the symbols `"CCO"` and three characters. That is SMILES. SMILES is a common language adopted by most databases and computational tools, including PubChem and ChEMBL.
%[text] In this script, you will work through a series of operations to analyze and draw molecules from SMILES.
%[text] **What you will learn in this tutorial**
%[text] - Understand the SMILES notation that represents molecular structures
%[text] - Convert SMILES to molecular objects using `emk.mol.fromSmiles`
%[text] - Draw 2D structural diagrams using `emk.viz.draw2d`
%[text] - Validate SMILES strings using `emk.mol.isValid`
%[text] - Convert to canonical SMILES using `emk.mol.toSmiles` \
%[text] **Requirements**
%[text] - RDKit installed (run `emk.setup.install()` once)
%[text] - No additional toolbox required (works with MATLAB only) \
%[text] Estimated time: 5–10 minutes | How to run: Execute each section one by one with Ctrl+Enter
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
%[text] Initialize the path and Python environment.
%[text] **Always run this section first.**
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:33734d2e]
%[text] Warm up the Python/RDKit process (the first call may take some time).
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane
clear mol_warmup;
logInfo("F01: Setup complete"); %[output:01b6cf4e]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Analyzing the First Molecule
%[text] Using `emk.mol.fromSmiles`, you can convert a SMILES string into a molecular object (`Mol`). The `Mol` object can be treated as a MATLAB variable and passed to all `emk.*` functions.
%[text] 
%[text] ### SMILES — How to Represent Molecules with "Characters"
%[text] Molecules are graphs made of atoms (points) and bonds (lines). SMILES traverses that graph in a depth-first manner and converts it into a string of atomic symbols. For example, `CCO` (ethanol) is the result of reading "carbon → carbon → oxygen." Molecules with rings indicate ring closures with numbers (`1`, `2`, ...). SMILES is a common language in cheminformatics, adopted by PubChem, ChEMBL, and most computational tools. It can be easily shared via copy and paste and used directly for database searches.
%[text] **Examples of SMILES**
%[text] - `"CCO"` — Ethanol
%[text] - `"c1ccccc1"` — Benzene (lowercase = aromatic)
%[text] - `"CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O"` — Aspirin \
mol_ethanol = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CCO");
logInfo("Ethanol analysis complete: class = %s", class(mol_ethanol)); %[output:09682f5e]
mol_aspirin = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O");
logInfo("Aspirin analysis complete: class = %s", class(mol_aspirin)); %[output:45f11fdb]
mol_caffeine = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C(=O)N2C)C");
logInfo("Caffeine analysis complete: class = %s", class(mol_caffeine)); %[output:8d5e25af]
%[text] 
