%[text] ## Section 2: Drawing 2D Structural Diagrams
%[text] Using `emk.viz.draw2d`, you can display the 2D structural diagram of a molecule in a MATLAB figure. RDKit generates a PNG image, and MATLAB draws it directly.
figure("Name", "Ethanol"); %[output:07336ad4]
emk.viz.draw2d(mol_ethanol, Title="Ethanol (CCO)"); %[output:07336ad4]
%[text] 
figure("Name", "Aspirin"); %[output:862daa93]
emk.viz.draw2d(mol_aspirin, Title="Aspirin (CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O)"); %[output:862daa93]
%[text] 
figure("Name", "Caffeine"); %[output:73239108]
emk.viz.draw2d(mol_caffeine, Title="Caffeine (CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C(=O)N2C)C)"); %[output:73239108]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Canonical SMILES
%[text] ### Why Normalization is Necessary
%[text] Even for the same molecule, it can be represented by different strings like `"CCO"`, `"OCC"`, or `"C(O)C"` depending on the order of the starting atoms. This makes it impossible to detect duplicates or search databases based on exact string matches. Therefore, RDKit uses a deterministic algorithm based on the Morgan algorithm (Morgan, 1965) to always output a unique "canonical SMILES" for any input representation. Using canonical SMILES allows you to safely treat molecules as primary keys in databases.
%[text] Let's verify this in practice.
variants = ["OCC", "CCO", "C(O)C"];   % All are ethanol
logInfo("--- Canonical SMILES for Each Ethanol Representation ---"); %[output:1fd0edac]
for i = 1:numel(variants) %[output:group:997b680a]
    mol  = emk.mol.fromSmiles(variants(i));
    can  = emk.mol.toSmiles(mol);
    logInfo("  Input: %-10s  ->  Canonical: %s", variants(i), can); %[output:94b001b5]
end %[output:group:997b680a]
%[text] All three will output the same canonical SMILES.
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 2 — Verify with Heterocyclic Compounds**
%[text] Check the canonical SMILES for `"c1ccncc1"` (pyridine) and `"c1ccoc1"` (furan).
%[text] - What canonical SMILES does RDKit output for each?
%[text] - Is the output in lowercase? (Lowercase = evidence that RDKit recognized it as aromatic) \
% ... (Try writing code here)
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Validating SMILES Strings
%[text] `emk.mol.isValid` returns `true` if the SMILES is chemically valid and `false` if invalid. It can be used as a first filter when dealing with user input or external data files.
%[text]  **Note**: Testing an invalid SMILES may display RDKit internal logs like `SMILES Parse Error: ...` in the console. This is normal behavior, and `isValid` will correctly return `false`.
test_cases = {"CCO", "c1ccccc1", "INVALID_XYZ", "", "C(C)(C)(C)(C)C"};
logInfo("--- SMILES Validation ---"); %[output:109ab757]
for i = 1:numel(test_cases) %[output:group:7ff1a2ca]
    tf    = emk.mol.isValid(test_cases{i});
    label = test_cases{i};
    if isempty(label), label = "(empty)"; end
    logInfo("  %-25s  isValid = %d", label, tf); %[output:6fea02de]
end %[output:group:7ff1a2ca]
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 3 — Investigate an Unexpected Result**
%[text] Passing `"C(C)(C)(C)(C)C"` (five bonds to carbon) will return `false`. Why is that?
%[text] Hint: SMILES does not treat five-coordinate carbon as a syntax error, but `isValid` checks for chemical validity (valence rules) and returns `false`.
% ... (Try writing code here)
%[text] Next, try the broken string `"C(CC"` (unclosed parentheses). What do you get?
% ... (Try writing code here)
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Batch Visualization
%[text] Using `subplot`, you can display multiple molecules in a grid within a single figure.
%[text] This is a useful pattern when you want to compare a small number of compounds.
smiles_list = ["CCO", "c1ccccc1", "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O", ...
               "CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C(=O)N2C)C"];
names       = ["Ethanol", "Benzene", "Aspirin", "Caffeine"];
figure("Name", "Molecule Grid", "Position", [100 100 800 700]); %[output:00df9e4e]
for i = 1:numel(smiles_list) %[output:group:7411b3f4]
    subplot(2, 2, i); %[output:00df9e4e]
    mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles(smiles_list(i));
    emk.viz.draw2d(mol, Title=names(i));
end %[output:group:7411b3f4]
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 4 — Expand the Grid**
%[text] Add your favorite molecule as the fifth entry and re-run this section.
%[text] Don't forget to adjust the size of the `subplot`.
%[text] Hint: For N entries, you can use a grid of `ceil(sqrt(N))` × `ceil(sqrt(N))`.
% ... (Try writing code here)
